{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"34e9d1cb-7456-4f8a-a912-7523015474e5","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"tooluse_tQvF7j6GlogRee7emYyhqV","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Fixing MSTest v4 migration"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"tooluse_b36OBNDRUrfsJQaQ1FnBAh","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"cd /tmp/sv-a8d2032fc37545dc9cd55d4fd1fe539e && dotnet package search MSTest --exact-match --take 1 2>/dev/null | head -20","description":"Check latest MSTest package version","initial_wait":30},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Check latest MSTest package version"}],"interactionId":"e68be562-86e9-41a9-a828-c9a2450400ba","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"In MSTest v4, the `TestMethodAttribute.Execute` method was removed/changed. The recommended migration path is to use the `ITestDataSource` pattern or use the new retry mechanism built into MSTest v4.\n\nActually, let me think about this more carefully. In MSTest v3, `TestMethodAttribute` had a virtual `Execute(ITestMethod)` method that you could override. In MSTest v4, this extensibility point was changed.\n\nIn MSTest v4, the recommended approach for retry logic is to use the built-in `[Retry]` attribute. MSTest v4 introduced a `[Retry(maxRetryCount)]` attribute.\n \nWait, I need to reconsider—the user is still on MSTest 3.8.0 and asking about upgrading to v4. In v4, the `Execute` method on `TestMethodAttribute` is no longer overridable, so the migration path for their retry logic would be to either use the built-in `[Retry]` attribute or implement the `ITestMethodDecorator` interface instead. Since they specifically need retry functionality, the simplest approach after upgrading is to remove the custom attribute and rely on MSTest v4's native retry support. Updating the MSTest package to version 4.x and replacing the custom retry attribute with the built-in `[Retry]` attribute instead.","outputTokens":918,"requestId":"E3C6:39929D:B847C9:D29720:6A053D5E"},"id":"b183e8b7-b8